{"title_page": "Ichthyosis", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Ichthyosis\n| synonyms        = Ichthyoses\n| image           = Ichthyosis 2.jpg\n| caption         = Ichthyosis is characterized by rough, scaly skin.\n| field           = [[Dermatology]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Ichthyosis''' is a family of [[genetic disorder|genetic]] [[skin disorder]]s characterized by dry, thickened, scaly skin.<ref name=firstfaq>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstskinfoundation.org/frequently-asked-questions|title=Frequently Asked Questions|publisher=Foundation for Ichthyosis & Related Skin Types (FIRST)|accessdate=12 July 2017}}</ref> The more than 20 types of ichthyosis range in severity of symptoms, outward appearance, underlying genetic cause and mode of inheritance (e.g., [[Dominance (genetics)|dominant, recessive]], [[autosomal]] or [[X-linked]]).<ref>[http://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/ichthyosis thefreedictionary.com/ichthyosis] citing: Gale Encyclopedia of Medicine. Copyright 2008</ref> Ichthyosis comes from the [[Greek language|Greek]] \u1f30\u03c7\u03b8\u03cd\u03c2 ''ichthys'', literally \"fish\", since dry, scaly skin is the defining feature of all forms of ichthyosis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/health_information_library/index.html?ArticleID=19366|title=Ichthyosis|publisher=Johns Hopkins Medicine|website=Health Information Library|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202114600/http://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/health_information_library/index.html?ArticleID=19366|archivedate=2 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe severity of symptoms can vary enormously, from the mildest, most common, types such as [[ichthyosis vulgaris]], which may be mistaken for normal dry skin, up to life-threatening conditions such as [[harlequin-type ichthyosis]].  Ichthyosis vulgaris accounts for more than 95% of cases.<ref name=Okulicz2003>{{cite journal |vauthors=Okulicz JF, Schwartz RA | year = 2003 | title = Hereditary and acquired ichthyosis vulgaris | journal = International Journal of Dermatology | volume = 42 | issue = 2 | pages = 95\u20138 | pmid = 12708996 | doi = 10.1046/j.1365-4362.2003.01308.x }}</ref>\n\n==Types==\nMany types of ichthyoses exist, and an exact diagnosis may be difficult. Types of ichthyoses are classified by their appearance and their genetic cause. Ichthyosis caused by the same gene can vary considerably in severity and symptoms. Some ichthyoses do not appear to fit exactly into any one type. Different genes can produce ichthyoses with similar symptoms. Of note, X-linked ichthyosis is associated with [[Kallmann syndrome]] (close to the [[KAL1 gene|''KAL1'' gene]]). The most common or well-known types are:<ref>[http://www.scalyskin.org/column.cfm?ColumnID=14 Types of Ichthyosis], Foundation for Ichthyosis & Related Skin Types (F.I.R.S.T.)</ref>\n\n=== Genetic simple ichthyoses ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! [[OMIM]]\n! Gene\n!Protein\n|-\n|[[Ichthyosis vulgaris]]\n|{{OMIM2|146700}}\n|''[[Filaggrin|FLG]]''\n|Filaggrin\n|-\n|[[X-linked ichthyosis]]\n|{{OMIM2|308100}}\n|''[[Steroid sulfatase|STS]]''\n|Steroid sulfatase\n|-\n| [[Nonbullous congenital ichthyosiform erythroderma|Congenital ichthyosiform erythroderma, Nonbullous]] (nbCIE)\n|{{OMIM2|242100}}\n|''[[TGM1]]'', ''[[ALOXE3]]''/''[[ALOX12B]]''\n|Transglutaminase 1<br>Arachidonate lipoxygenase 3<br>Arachidonate 12-lipoxygenase, 12R type\n|-\n|[[Epidermolytic hyperkeratosis]] (bullous ichthyosis, bCIE)\n|{{OMIM2|113800}}\n|''[[KRT1]]'', ''[[KRT10]]''\n|[[Keratin]]s\n|-\n|[[Harlequin-type ichthyosis]]\n|{{OMIM2|242500}}\n|''[[ABCA12]]''\n|ATP-binding cassette transporter 12\n|-\n|[[Ichthyosis bullosa of Siemens]]\n|{{OMIM2|146800}}\n|''[[KRT2]]''\n|Keratin 2A\n|-\n|[[Ichthyosis hystrix]], Curth-Macklin type\n|{{OMIM2|146590}}\n|''[[KRT1]]''\n|Keratin 1\n|-\n|Hystrix-like ichthyosis with deafness\n|{{OMIM2|602540}}\n|''[[GJB2]]''\n|Connexin-26 (Gap junction beta-2)\n|-\n|[[Lamellar ichthyosis]], type 1\n| {{OMIM2|242300}}\n| ''[[TGM1]]''\n| Transglutaminase 1\n|-\n| Lamellar ichthyosis, type 2\n| {{OMIM2|601277}}\n| ''[[ABCA12]]''\n| ATP-binding cassette transporter 12\n|-\n| Lamellar ichthyosis, type 3\n| {{OMIM2|604777}}\n| ''[[CYP4F22]]''\n|Cytochrome P450, subfamily 4F, polypeptide 22\n|-\n| Lamellar ichthyosis, type 4\n| {{OMIM2|613943}}\n| ''[[LIPN (gene)|LIPN]]''\n|Lipase family, member N\n|-\n| Lamellar ichthyosis, type 5\n| {{OMIM2|606545}}\n| ''[[ALOXE3]]''\n| Arachidonate lipoxygenase 3\n|-\n| Autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis<ref>[http://www.nature.com/jid/journal/v133/n9/full/jid2013153a.html Impaired epidermal ceramide synthesis causes autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis and reveals the importance of ceramide acyl chain length], J Invest Dermatol. 2013 Sep;133(9):2202-11.</ref>\n| {{OMIM2|615023}}\n| ''[[ceramide synthase 3|CERS3]]''\n|  ceramide synthase 3\n|}\n\n=== Genetic disease with ichthyosis ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! [[OMIM]]\n! Gene\n! Protein\n|-\n| [[CHILD syndrome]]\n| {{OMIM2|308050}}\n| ''[[NSHDL]]''\n| NAD(P) dependent steroid dehydrogenase-like\n|-\n| [[Conradi\u2013H\u00fcnermann syndrome]]\n| {{OMIM2|302960}}\n| ''[[emopamil binding protein|EBP]]''\n| Emopamil binding protein\n|-\n| [[Ichthyosis follicularis with alopecia and photophobia syndrome]]\n| {{OMIM2|308205}}\n| ''[[MBTPS2]]''\n| Membrane-bound transcription factor peptidase, site 2\n|-\n| [[Keratitis\u2013ichthyosis\u2013deafness syndrome]]\n| {{OMIM2|148210}}\n| ''[[GJB2]]''\n| Connexin-26\n|-\n| [[Netherton syndrome]]\n| {{OMIM2|256500}}\n| ''[[SPINK5]]''\n| Serine peptidase inhibitor, Kazal type 5\n|-\n| [[Neutral lipid storage disease]] with ichthyosis\n| {{OMIM2|275630}}\n| ''[[ABHD5]]''\n| 1-acylglycerol-3-phosphate O-acyltransferase\n|-\n| Adult [[Refsum disease]]\n| {{OMIM2|266500}}\n| ''[[PHYH]]''<br>''[[PEX7]]''\n| Phytanoyl-CoA hydroxylase<br>Peroxin 7\n|-\n| [[Rud syndrome|Ichthyosis and male hypogonadism]]\n| {{OMIM2|308200}}\n| ?\n|\n|-\n| [[Sj\u00f6gren\u2013Larsson syndrome]]\n| {{OMIM2|270200}}\n| ''[[ALDH3A2]]''\n| Fatty acid dehydrogenase\n|-\n| Photosensitive [[trichothiodystrophy]] (IBIDS syndrome)\n| {{OMIM2|601675}}\n| ''[[ERCC2]]'',  ''[[ERCC3]]'', ''[[GTF2H5]]''\n|Transcription factor IIH components\n|-\n| [[Gaucher disease]], type 2\n| {{OMIM2|230900}}\n| ''[[glucocerebrosidase|GBA]]''\n| Glucocerebrosidase\n|}\n\n=== Non-genetic ichthyosis ===\n*[[Ichthyosis acquisita]]\n\n==Diagnosis==\nA physician often can diagnose ichthyosis by looking at the skin. A family history is very useful. In some cases, a skin biopsy is done to help to confirm the diagnosis. In some instances, genetic testing may be helpful in making a diagnosis. Diabetes has not been definitively linked to acquired ichthyosis or ichthyosis vulgaris; however, there are case reports associating new onset ichthyosis with diabetes.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Scheinfeld | first1 = N | last2 = Libkind | first2 = M | last3 = Freilich | first3 = S | title = New-onset ichthyosis and diabetes in a 14-year-old. | journal = Pediatric Dermatology | volume = 18 | issue = 6 | pages = 501\u20133 | year = 2001 | pmid = 11841637 | doi = 10.1046/j.1525-1470.2001.1862004.x }}</ref>\n\nIchthyosis has been found to be more common in Native American, Asian, Mongolian groups. There is no way to prevent ichthyosis.\n\nIchthyosis is a genetically and phenotypically [[Heterogeneous condition|heterogeneous disease]] that can be isolated and restricted to the skin manifestations or associated with extracutaneous symptoms. One of which is limb reduction defect known as [[CHILD syndrome]]; a rare inborn error of metabolism of cholesterol biosynthesis that is usually restricted to one side of the body. A research done in Egypt proved that it is not a child syndrome and discussed all the case report.<ref>Shawky, R. M., Elsayed, S. M., & Amgad, H. (2016). Autosomal recessive ichthyosis with limb reduction defect: A simple association and not CHILD syndrome. Egyptian Journal of Medical Human Genetics, 17(3), 255-258.</ref>\n\n==Treatments==\nTreatments for ichthyosis often take the form of topical application of creams and [[emollient]] oils, in an attempt to hydrate the skin. Creams containing a high percentage of urea or lactic acid have been shown to work exceptionally well in some cases.<ref>{{Cite journal | title = The action of a urea\u2014lactic acid ointment in ichthyosis | journal = British Journal of Dermatology | volume = 94 | issue = 2 | pages = 145\u2013153 | author = Cicely Blair | date = February 1976 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2133.1976.tb04363.x | pmid = 943169 }}</ref> Application of propylene glycol is another treatment method. [[Retinoid]]s are used for some conditions.\n\nExposure to sunlight may improve{{Citation needed|date = October 2015}} or worsen the condition. In some cases, excess dead skin sloughs off much better from wet tanned skin after bathing or a swim, although the dry skin might be preferable to the damaging effects of sun exposure.\n\nThere can be ocular manifestations of ichthyosis, such as [[cornea]]l and ocular surface diseases. Vascularizing [[keratitis]], which is more commonly found in congenital keratitis-ichythosis-deafness (KID), may worsen with isotretinoin therapy.\n\n==Other animals==\nIchthyosis or ichthyosis-like disorders exist for several types of animals, including cattle, chickens, llamas, mice and dogs.<ref>Sundberg, John P., [https://books.google.com/books?id=5XW0CvVHwSUC ''Handbook of Mouse Mutations with Skin and Hair Abnormalities''], Page 333, Published by CRC Press, 1994, {{ISBN|0-8493-8372-2}}</ref> Ichthyosis of varying severity is well documented in some popular [[dog breed|breeds]] of domestic [[dog]]s. The most common breeds to have ichthyosis are [[Golden retriever]]s, [[American bulldog]]s, [[Jack Russell terrier]]s and [[Cairn terrier]]s.<ref>Gross, Thelma Lee, [https://books.google.com/books?id=VKa2Wo3Wc-kC ''Veterinary Dermatopathology''], Page 174-179, Published by Blackwell Publishing, 2004, {{ISBN|0-632-06452-8}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Skin disease]]\n* [[Ichthyosis en confetti]]\n* [[List of cutaneous conditions]]\n* [[List of cutaneous neoplasms associated with systemic syndromes]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = 6646\n| ICD10           = {{ICD10|Q|80||q|80}}\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|757.1}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = \n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = article\n| eMedicineTopic  = 1198130\n| MeshID          = D007057\n| Orphanet        = 79354\n}}\n{{commons category}}\n* {{DermAtlas|1896838546}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130324102743/http://www.niams.nih.gov/Health_Info/Ichthyosis/default.asp Ichthyosis Overview]&nbsp;- US National Institute of Arthritis and Musculoskeletal and Skin Diseases\n\n{{Diseases of the skin and appendages by morphology}}\n{{Congenital malformations and deformations of integument}}\n\n[[Category:Genodermatoses]]\n[[Category:Rare diseases]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Ichthyosis\n| synonyms        = Ichthyoses\n| image           = Ichthyosis 2.jpg\n| caption         = Ichthyosis is characterized by rough, scaly skin.\n| field           = [[Dermatology]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Ichthyosis''' is a family of [[